csrf : A CSRF token is a unique, secret, and unpredictable value generated by a server to prevent Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF) attacks.


Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF) is a type of web security attack where a malicious attacker tricks a user's browser into making an unauthorized, state-changing request on a web application where the user is currently authenticated. 



Difference between include and require

require-> will produce a fatal error (E_COMPILE_ERROR) and stop the script.
include-> will only produce a warning (E_WARNING) and the script will continue.


require_once: If the specified file is not found, require_once will issue a fatal error (E_COMPILE_ERROR) and halt the script's execution immediately.
include_once: If the specified file is not found, include_once will issue a warning (E_WARNING), but the script will continue execution.


