1)Abstract class
An abstract class is a restricted class in object-oriented programming that serves as a blueprint for other classes and cannot be instantiated directly.


2)Encapsulation
Wrapping data and its member functions into a single entity is known as encapsulation. 

3)static class

These are regular PHP classes where all properties and methods are declared as static using the static keyword.




7)Primary key, Unique Key, Foreign Key
A primary key is used to uniquely identify each record in a database table, preventing duplicate entries and ensuring data integrity.
 
A foreign key is a column or a set of columns in one table that establishes a link to the primary key of another table, enforcing referential integrity between the two tables.

A unique key is a column or a set of columns in a database table that enforces uniqueness, ensuring that no two rows have the same value(s) in those columns, except for NULL values.


8)Global variables
Some predefined variables in PHP are "superglobals", which means that they are always accessible, regardless of scope.

$_SERVER
$_REQUEST
$_POST
$_GET
$_FILES
$_COOKIE
$_SESSION

